<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1212,2028]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,1391]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="105" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,301,1212,1237]" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">Recognition.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Robineau-Desvoidy" authorityYear="1830" box="[308,465,1212,1237]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Leschenaultia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[308,465,1212,1237]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">Leschenaultia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, including the new species described here, share the following combination of features. Head (
<figureCitation box="[334,399,1247,1272]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1963,1986]" captionTargetBox="[207,1377,243,1868]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[176,1411,175,1992]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Leschenaultia belkysae sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 1. Habitus, lateral view. 2. Habitus, dorsal view. 3. Head, lateral view. 4. Wing, dorsal view. 5. Abdomen, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1.00 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2628669/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">Fig 3</figureCitation>
): fronto-orbital plate of male with a pair of reclinate orbital setae and without proclinate orbital setae (female with two pairs of proclinate orbital setae); ocellar seta short or well-developed and slightly divergent; inner vertical seta parallel; outer vertical seta reduced and almost undifferentiated from postocular setae in male, sometimes longer in female; parafacial bare below level of lowermost frontal seta; facial ridge with a row of supravibrissal setae ranging from 0.5 to 0.6 of facial ridge length, bordered by smaller and weaker setae and setulae; lower facial margin in profile slightly projected. Torax (
<figureCitation box="[865,966,1426,1451]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1963,1986]" captionTargetBox="[207,1377,243,1868]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[176,1411,175,1992]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Leschenaultia belkysae sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 1. Habitus, lateral view. 2. Habitus, dorsal view. 3. Head, lateral view. 4. Wing, dorsal view. 5. Abdomen, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1.00 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2628669/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">Figs 1, 2</figureCitation>
): acrostichal setae 3+3; dorsocentral setae 3+4; intra-alar setae 2+3; supra-alar setae 2+3; three postalar setae, the second one stronger and longer; intrapostalar seta short; katepisternum with three setae, anterior and posterior katepisternal setae longer and stronger than anteroventral katepisternal seta; scutellum with one pair of basal, two pairs of lateral, one pair of subapical, one pair of apical and one pair of discal setae, and a group of setulae between discal setae; first lateral scutellar seta slightly shorter than second lateral scutellar seta; apical scutellar setae short but longer than setulae on scutellar dorsum. Wing (
<figureCitation box="[435,501,1640,1665]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1963,1986]" captionTargetBox="[207,1377,243,1868]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[176,1411,175,1992]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Leschenaultia belkysae sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 1. Habitus, lateral view. 2. Habitus, dorsal view. 3. Head, lateral view. 4. Wing, dorsal view. 5. Abdomen, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1.00 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2628669/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">Fig 4</figureCitation>
): usually subhyaline with basal fourth infuscate; wing venation constant: cell r 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1412,1436,1655,1669]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">4+5</subScript>
open with veins R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[355,379,1694,1708]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">4+5</subScript>
and M ending anterior to wing apex; apical section of vein M bent sharply forward. Leg: mid tibia with three to eight stout anterodorsal setae; hind tibia with a row of depressed anterodorsal setae, each seta separated from adjacent seta by no more than its own width. Abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[1017,1083,1753,1778]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1963,1986]" captionTargetBox="[207,1377,243,1868]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[176,1411,175,1992]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Leschenaultia belkysae sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 1. Habitus, lateral view. 2. Habitus, dorsal view. 3. Head, lateral view. 4. Wing, dorsal view. 5. Abdomen, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1.00 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2628669/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">Fig 5</figureCitation>
): abdominal setulae gradually increasing in size posteriorly, more visible and denser on sides of tergite 4. Male terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[1204,1322,1789,1814]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 6–8" captionStart-1="FIGURES 9–14" captionStart-2="FIGURES 15–23" captionStartId-0="6.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionStartId-1="7.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionStartId-2="8.[151,264,1838,1861]" captionTargetBox-0="[212,1354,306,1811]" captionTargetBox-1="[206,1400,243,1825]" captionTargetBox-2="[326,1247,272,1768]" captionTargetId-0="figure@6.[151,1436,260,1826]" captionTargetId-1="figure@7.[166,1430,193,1892]" captionTargetId-2="figure@8.[237,1354,178,1822]" captionTargetPageId-0="6" captionTargetPageId-1="7" captionTargetPageId-2="8" captionText-0="FIGURES 6–8. Leschenaultia andarae sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 6. Male terminalia, lateral view. 7. Sternites 5–6 and syntergosternite 7+8, anterodorsal view. 8. Hypandrium, posteroventral view. Abbreviations: aed apod, aedeagal apodeme; cerc, cercus; distph, distiphallus; epiph, epiphallus; hypd, hypandrium; hypd a, hypandrial arm; hypd apod, hypandrial apodeme; postg, postgonite; preg, pregonite; st, sternite; sur, surstylus; syntgst, syntergosternite Scale bars: 0.25 mm." captionText-1="FIGURES 9–14. Leschenaultia spp. 9–13. Male terminalia, lateral view. 14. Sternite 5, ventral view. 9. Leschenaultia andarae sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 10. Leschenaultia belkysae sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 11. Leschenaultia frangeri sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 12. Leschenaultia liriai sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 13. Leschenaultia marjorieae sp. n. paratype ♂ (MZUSP). 14. Leschenaultia frangeri sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). Scale bars: 0.25 mm." captionText-2="FIGURES 15–23. Leschenaultia spp. 15–19. Male terminalia, posterior view. 20–23. Female from Mato Grosso, Chapada dos Guimarães, 21.i.2012 (MZUSP). 15. Leschenaultia andarae sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 16. Leschenaultia belkysae sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 17. Leschenaultia frangeri sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 18. Leschenaultia liriai sp. n. holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 19. Leschenaultia marjorieae sp. n. paratype ♂ (MZUSP). 20. Spermathecae. 21. Terminalia, dorsal view. 22. Terminalia, lateral view. 23. Terminalia, ventral view. Abbreviations: cerc, cercus; epiprct, epiproct; hyprct, hypoproct; st, sternite; tg, tergite. Scale bars: 0.25 mm." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/2628671/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/2628673/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/2628679/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="104">Figs 6–19</figureCitation>
): tergite 6 reduced, with spiracles situated laterally on membrane; sternite 6 asymmetric and narrow, its left margin wider than its right margin, both margins connected to segment 7+8, the left margin slightly fused and the right margin connected by a membrane; hind margin of sternite 6 with two protrusions; sternite 5 with median cleft U-shaped; epandrium, in lateral view, with anterodorsal margin slightly convex, and posterior dorsolateral and ventrolateral margins extending into a triangular lobe; anterior epandrial extension developed; hypandrial apodeme moderately elongated in ventral view; well-marked dividing line between hypandrial apodeme and hypandrial middle plate, the former slightly narrower than the latter; hypandrial arms separated and narrow; pregonite tapering and slightly curved outward and downward, with a row of setulae gradually diminishing in size apically; postgonite shorter than pregonite and slightly clavate and curved downward; epiphallus lobe-like; cercus and surstylus relatively elongate and tapering; cercus in profile with variable curvature; surstylus in profile tapering in basal half and digitiform in apical half; in posterior view, cercus tapering from base to apex, joined along basal half; in posterior view, surstylus flattened. Female terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[481,613,330,355]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–23" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1838,1861]" captionTargetBox="[326,1247,272,1768]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[237,1354,178,1822]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 15–23. Leschenaultia spp. 15–19. Male terminalia, posterior view. 20–23. Female from Mato Grosso, Chapada dos Guimarães, 21.i.2012 (MZUSP). 15. Leschenaultia andarae sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 16. Leschenaultia belkysae sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 17. Leschenaultia frangeri sp. n., holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 18. Leschenaultia liriai sp. n. holotype ♂ (MZUSP). 19. Leschenaultia marjorieae sp. n. paratype ♂ (MZUSP). 20. Spermathecae. 21. Terminalia, dorsal view. 22. Terminalia, lateral view. 23. Terminalia, ventral view. Abbreviations: cerc, cercus; epiprct, epiproct; hyprct, hypoproct; st, sternite; tg, tergite. Scale bars: 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2628679/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="105">Figs 20–23</figureCitation>
): tergite 6 divided and connected by a membrane in the middle; sternite 6 large and subrectangular; tergite 7 completely divided, longer than wide; sternite 7 of irregular pentagonal shape; tergite 8 divided into two narrow parts; sternite 8 small; epiproct small, slightly sclerotized or reduced; hypoproct U-shaped with a posterior lobe at middle, proximal portion of arms folded ventrally; three piriform spermathecae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
